{"actor":{"id":"claude-fable-5","type":"agent"},"content":{"blocks":[{"text":"Conversation Ledger is real. `cledger` 0.1.0 is built, tested (46/46), globally installed, and hooked into both coding CLIs — it captured this very conversation as its first proof.\n\n## What exists now\n\nA zero-dependency TypeScript/Node CLI (installed as both `cledger` and `conversation-ledger`) implementing the design docs' commitments: immutable `EvidenceEvent`s with content-derived ids, six open-ended kinds (`conversation_turn` is just one — a bare `decision` event flowed through untouched in testing), full provenance (repo, branch, HEAD, dirty-tree fingerprint, actor, producer, timestamps), and lossless `raw` retention of native transcript lines. Commands: `append` (JSONL on stdin — any tool can write events), `log`, `show`, `conversations`, `export`, `sync`, `capture` (backfill), `install`, `hook`.\n\n**Storage** ended up as your original notes instinct, refined: one note per anchor commit under `refs/notes/conversation-ledger`, all content inline in the note (GC-safe, nothing outside git), canonical-JSON sorted-unique lines so git's `cat_sort_uniq` strategy merges concurrent appends conflict-free. Verified end-to-end: feature-branch conversations are invisible from `main` until you merge, then ride in with the merge; `git status` stays clean; sync is explicit and round-trips between clones including divergent appends.\n\n**Idempotency is the load-bearing property**: event ids hash only the source-determined fields, so hooks can naively re-scan transcripts forever — reruns produced +0 events every time. Cursors under `.git/conversation-ledger/` are pure optimization.\n\n## Two activation steps remain — both yours\n\n1. **Codex**: open `codex`, run `/hooks`, approve the `cledger hook codex` command. Codex 0.144 refuses to run unreviewed hooks (I also had to add `features.hooks = true`, which the installer now handles). Until then Codex capture is dormant — though `cledger capture codex --transcript <rollout>` backfills anything missed, as proven against 493 events from your live ds4-gateway session.\n2. **Claude Code**: hooks load at session start, so capture begins with your next session. This session's 164 events are already in this repo's ledger via a simulated hook call — sitting in the pending queue, because **this repo has no commits yet**. Your first commit will anchor them. (I didn't commit anything per standing rules — say the word and I'll make the initial commit.)\n\nBackups: `~/.claude/settings.json.bak-2026-07-18T22-47-57` and `~/.codex/config.toml.bak-...`; all your existing settings were preserved.\n\n## Honest caveats\n\n- **Squash merges** orphan conversations from the target branch's reachability view (events survive, `log --all` sees them; `re-anchor` is the documented future fix).\n- **Redaction** is append-a-redaction-event only; true content purge tooling is an open question, documented.\n- `capture --transcript` doesn't check that a transcript belongs to the repo you're in — deliberate (backfill/import freedom), but worth knowing.\n- Codex's encrypted reasoning is never stored; Claude's visible thinking text is (signatures stripped) — flag if you'd rather drop it entirely.\n\nDocs (`README`, `WIP_TECHNICAL_DESIGN`) now record all decisions and rationale. Subagent usage as requested: two Haiku explorers, one Haiku web-checker, and three Sonnet agents (research, adapters, tests) did the bulk of token-heavy work — roughly 300k subagent tokens that stayed out of this context.","type":"text"}],"role":"assistant"},"context":{"cwd":"/Users/evintunador/repos/evintunador/conversation-ledger","dirty_fingerprint":"e12e6fe04f3a78e3a5f3ff041be237d2a899e1d55f1148de6f18442622160697","repo":"conversation-ledger"},"conversation":{"id":"claude-code:700cd82f-2f79-4cd6-b727-0f81230e0837","seq":366},"id":"ev1-d3f4c2ae2e01d03a72e2462e52a778d4f3bc7015dfd7cc0d7bf2ab74ba9995a3","kind":"conversation_turn","occurred_at":"2026-07-18T22:57:53.488Z",