{"actor":{"id":"claude-fable-5","type":"agent"},"content":{"blocks":[{"text":"Everything's done. Here's the full picture, including answers to your two questions.\n\n## Your questions answered\n\n**Squash merges, concretely:** `cledger log` decides \"which conversations belong to this branch\" by asking git \"is the anchor commit reachable from HEAD?\" A normal merge makes the feature branch's commits ancestors of `main`, so their conversations appear. A *squash* merge never adds those commits to `main` — it creates one brand-new commit with the combined diff, and the original feature commits (which the notes are attached to) stay outside `main`'s ancestry forever. The events are **not lost** — they're still in the notes ref, and `cledger log --all` shows them — they just stop showing up in `main`'s branch-scoped view, because the commits they're pinned to were never merged. That's why the roadmap has `re-anchor`: reattach those events to the squash commit. If you mostly squash-merge on GitHub, this matters to you; if you use true merges, it never comes up.\n\n**Transcript→repo routing:** you're misunderstanding, and your instinct is exactly what's implemented. The automatic hook path records by the session's `cwd`: start a convo in repo A and use it to poke at repo B, and everything lands in **repo A's ledger only** — no magic, no double-recording. The caveat applied only to the *manual backfill command*: `cledger capture --transcript PATH` writes to whatever repo you're currently standing in, and doesn't cross-check that the transcript's own `cwd` field matches. That's how I imported your ds4-gateway session into a throwaway scratch repo during testing — I pointed at a foreign transcript on purpose and it obeyed. That's arguably correct (\"you asked, we did\" — it's also how you'd deliberately migrate history), but if you want I can add a non-blocking warning when the transcript's recorded cwd resolves to a *different* git repo. Nothing ever records to two repos.\n\n## Everything else from your list\n\n- **Activation verified**: your `/hooks` approval took — I ran a fresh `codex exec` and its session auto-captured into the ledger (new session id, 6 events). Claude Code capture starts with your next session.\n- **Adapter matrix** is now in the README: supported today = Claude Code (CLI + VS Code/JetBrains extensions + desktop-app local sessions — all share the same settings and transcripts) and Codex CLI. TODO list added: Gemini CLI, Kimi, Copilot CLI, Factory droid, Qwen Code, opencode, cursor-agent, aider, Goose/Amp — ordered by how ledger-friendly their storage/hooks look.\n- **GUI wrappers**: yes, largely — your hunch is right. The Codex desktop app shares the same `config.toml`, hooks engine, and rollout files as the CLI (confirmed by a bug that broke hooks in both at once), though OpenAI has open issues about the desktop app sometimes failing to load user config, and IDE-extension sessions reportedly may not fire hooks. Claude Code's desktop app and IDE extensions are officially documented as sharing the CLI's settings/hooks/history. Cloud-side execution (Codex cloud tasks, Claude \"Remote\" sessions, Cowork) runs on provider servers and can't be hooked locally — and either way, anything that produces a local transcript file can always be backfilled with `cledger capture`.\n- **Redaction TODO** added as the top roadmap item in README and expanded in the design doc: detect/scrub API keys and credentials in tool output *before* events are written — tool output is the riskiest content and is currently stored verbatim.\n- **Reasoning policy** codified in both docs exactly as you stated: record it when the provider exposes it (Claude thinking text, minus signatures), don't bother when they withhold it (Codex's encrypted payloads are skipped, never reconstructed).\n\nWant the cross-repo warning on manual `capture`? It's a five-line change — say the word.","type":"text"}],"role":"assistant"},"context":{"cwd":"/Users/evintunado