ns. Sticky Note captures session threads (files touched, narrative, failed approaches, conversation prompts, status) and surfaces relevant prior work to teammates automatically.\n\n**Core tagline:** \"Human-to-human handoff for AI coding assistants\" — metadata and context sharing between coding sessions across a team.\n\n---\n\n### 2. How It Stores Data\n\n**Primary storage:** `.git/sticky-note/` (inside the `.git` directory, branch-independent)\n\n- **sticky-note.json** — Central thread ledger with per-thread metadata: status (open/stuck/stale/closed/expired), author, files touched, narrative, failed approaches, work type, conversation prompts, resume chain, contributor list\n- **audit/<username>.jsonl** — Per-user JSONL audit trail (one JSON object per line) tracking tool usage, files modified, session IDs\n- **presence/<username>.json** — Per-user presence files showing who's active and what files they're working on\n- **Git Notes storage** — Session attribution stored in `refs/notes/sticky-note` for line-level git blame attribution (survives rebase/amend)\n\n**Advanced design (v3.0.0):** Uses a dedicated orphan branch **`sticky-note/data`** to hold all thread metadata separate from feature branches. Eliminates two critical failure modes: branch time-travel (old .sticky-note.json on branch checkout) and write-race corruption (file truncation during pre-commit hook on Windows). Data syncs at session start (fetch) and end (commit+push to the data branch).\n\n**Merge strategy:** Custom git merge driver (`merge=sticky-note`) performs field-level 3-way merge on threads by ID rather than line-based union, handling concurrent edits intelligently.\n\n---\n\n### 3. CLI/API Surface & Design Philosophy\n\n**Unix-style composable philosophy:** Sticky Note follows minimal CLI design with powerful read/query commands, no destructive defaults, and composable hooks into the AI assistant workflow.\n\n**Main commands:**\n- `init` — Interactive setup (installs hooks, templates, data branch)\n- `threads` / `audit` / `who` — Read-only queries (list threads, filter by user/file/time, show presence)\n- `resume <id>` / `resume-thread --query \"...\"` — Thread handoff across tools\n- `overlap` / `claim` — Explicit conflict detection before editing\n- `sync` — Manual commit/push of `.git/sticky-note/` to remote\n- `status` / `gc` / `reset` — Diagnostics and cleanup\n- `get-line-attribution --file <path>` — Map file lines to originating threads\n- `mcp-server` — Exposes 8-tool MCP server (get_session_context, search_threads, check_overlaps, get_audit_trail, etc.)\n\n**Hook architecture:** Five collection hooks + one injection hook + one pre-tool-use hook:\n- **Collectors:** `track-work.js` (audit on tool use), `session-end.js` (capture thread on exit), `on-error.js` (mark stuck), `on-stop.js` (handoff summary)\n- **Injectors:** `session-start.js` (eager injection at boot), `inject-context.js` (relevance scoring on each prompt), `pre-tool-use.js` (lazy git-blame-driven injection)\n\n**Design principles:**\n- **No code capture** — Only metadata (files, timestamps, narrative summaries, error patterns)\n- **Git-native** — No external DB; all data versioned in git; merge driver handles concurrent teams\n- **Offline-safe** — Local cache in `.git/sticky-note/`, syncs when connectivity available\n- **Tool-agnostic** — Same hook scripts work across Claude Code, Copilot CLI, Codex; MCP server for third-party tools\n- **Unix philosophy** — Small, single-purpose commands; composable; reads from files; no hidden state\n\n---\n\n### 4. Maturity Level\n\n**Production-ready with sophisticated architecture:**\n- **Version 3.0.0** (released) with major v3 redesign (data-branch storage)\n- **Working codebase** in Node.js 16+, not design docs; active development (commits through 2026-07)\n- **~170MB repo** with comprehensive documentation, design specs, templates, example demo threads\n- **Test coverage** — Smoke tests in `test/smoke.test.js` (CLI command non-crash verification)\n- **Public on npm** — `sticky-note-cli` available via `npx`; used in production by teams\n- **Maintained** — Recent refactors, bug fixes (write-race fix, stale hook path detection), v3.0 migration support\n- **Rich docs** — README (23KB), CLAUDE.md (10KB), 10+ design/feature docs (branch-switching, MCP server, thread resume, smart injection, etc.)\n- **Change log** — CHANGELOG.md with per-version feature/fix breakdown\n\n---\n\n### 5. Relevance to conversation-ledger\n\n**Strong structural parallels; sticky-note is a template for how to build conversation-ledger:**\n\n| Aspect | sticky-note | conversation-ledger (planned) |\n|--------|------------|------------------------------|\n| **Core data** | Session threads (AI context metadata) | Conversation transcripts (AI→human handoff) |\n| **Storage** | Git-backed `.git/sticky-note/` branch | Git-backed append-only store (you're designing) |\n| **Distribution** | Team shared via git; no external DB | Solo/team shared via git; append-only |\n| **Interface** | CLI + hooks + MCP server | CLI + git plumbing (you're building) |\n| **Philosophy** | Unix-composition; metadata only | Unix-composition; transcript log format |\n| **Conflict resolution** | Custom merge driver (3-way field-merge) | Append-only negates conflicts |\n| **Offline-first** | Local cache, sync on session end | Local first; push on demand |\n\n**Why sticky-note is relevant:**\n\n1. **Prior art on git-backed metadata storage** — Shows how to store semantic data (not just source code) in git without triggering merge conflicts or write races. The data-branch design elegantly separates concerns.\n\n2. **Hook-driven architecture** — Demonstrates inserting capture logic into AI tool workflows without modifying the tools themselves. Could inform conversation-ledger's hook/signal story.\n\n3. **Relevance scoring & injection** — Three-tier attribution (git notes → audit JSONL → file+date heuristic) is sophisticated pattern for \"what context is relevant 