{"actor":{"type":"human"},"content":{"blocks":[{"content":[{"text":"Based on the research, here's how OpenAI Codex CLI 0.144.x hook trust system works:\n\n## How Users Persist Trust\n\nUsers review and approve hooks through the `/hooks` command in the CLI. Trust is persisted locally against each hook's hash. When a hook is modified or new, it's marked for review again. The system requires explicit user approval before non-managed hooks can execute.\n\n## `codex exec` Behavior\n\n`codex exec` **cannot** run newly-added hooks without either user review/trust or the `--dangerously-bypass-hook-trust` flag. Non-managed hooks are skipped until trusted. The `--dangerously-bypass-hook-trust` flag is strictly for one-off automation scenarios where hook sources are already vetted externally. In version 0.144.x, hook trust bypass now persists through `codex exec` thread start and resume operations (per PR #26434).\n\n## `features.hooks` Gating\n\nYes, `features.hooks` is still required in 0.144.x. It must be enabled in `~/.codex/config.toml` for hooks functionality; the feature is **off by default** and hooks are silently ignored without it. However, managed hooks from system, MDM, cloud, or enterprise sources bypass user review requirements and are automatically trusted by policy.\n\n## Summary\n\nHook trust is an interactive approval process via `/hooks`, not automatic. New hooks always require review unless they're managed (enterprise/system) or you use `--dangerously-bypass-hook-trust`. The `features.hooks` config flag must be explicitly enabled.\n\n---\n\n**Sources:**\n- [Hooks | ChatGPT Learn](https://learn.chatgpt.com/docs/hooks)\n- [Config Reference | ChatGPT Learn](https://learn.chatgpt.com/docs/config-file/config-reference)\n- [Release 0.144.0 | OpenAI/Codex](https://github.com/openai/codex/releases/tag/rust-v0.144.0)\n- [PR #26434: Preserve hook trust bypass in codex exec threads](https://github.com/openai/codex/pull/26434)","type":"text"},{"text":"agentId: a64e77f6